{
  "texts": [
    "In the τ th pulse, the transmit signal can be formulated asx r (τ, t) = Nt n=1 w n φ n (t) = W φ(t),(1)where t stands for the fast time index, φ n (t) stands for the nth orthogonal waveform, w n ∈ C Nt×1 refers to the beamforming vector,φ(t) = [φ 1 (t),..., φ Nt (t)] T ∈ C Nt×1, and W = [w 1,..., w Nt] ∈ C Nt×Nt.Assuming that one narrowband far-field target of interest is located in the radar mainlobe, the received signal can be formulated asy r (t, τ) = Nt n=1 β(τ)φ n (t -∆)e j2πf d t a(N r, θ)a H (N t, θ)w n + z(t, τ),(2)where β(τ), ∆ = 2d c, f d = 2v λ, θ, and θ represent the complex reflection coefficient, propagation delay, Doppler frequency shift, angle-of-arrival (AoA), and angle-of-departure (AoD) corresponding to the target, respectively.",
    "The parameters d and v refer to the distance and velocity of the target, respectively, while c, λ, and z(t, τ) ∈ C Nr×1 denote the speed of light, wavelength, and additive white Gaussian noise (AWGN), respectively.",
    "a(N, θ) ∈ C N ×1 stands for the steering vector of an N -antenna ULA towards the angle θ, which can be written as a(N, θ) = 1, e jπ sin θ,..., e jπ(N -1) sin θ T.The target detection problem can be modeled as the following binary hypothesis testing [84]: where y target (t, τ)y r (t, τ) = z(t, τ), H 0, y r (t, τ) = y target (t, τ) + z(t, τ), H 1,(4)Nt n=1 β(τ)φ n (t-∆)e j2πf d t a(N r, θ)•a H (N t, θ)w n represents the noise-free echo signal.",
    "H 0 refers to the null hypothesis that the target is absent and H 1 denotes the alternative hypothesis that the target is present.Generally, a radar utilizes a detector Λ(•), such as the generalized likelihood ratio test [85], to map the received echo signal to a positive real number.",
    "By comparing the mapped value with the detection threshold, the radar can determine whether the target is present or not."
  ]
}